<TEXT>
former president richard nixon who reopened 
ties with china in the 1970s is planning to visit china in 
september according to a published report 
us officials and diplomatic sources were quoted in saturdays 
editions of the washington post as saying that nixon and former 
secretary of state henry kissinger were likely to be among the first 
prominent americans to visit china since the bloody crackdown on 
prodemocracy demonstrators last month 
nixon did not respond to inquiries about his china plans the 
newspaper said 
kissinger who served under nixon and helped forge relations with 
china was quoted as saying he was considering a longstanding 
invitation to visit china in october to take part in a 
governmentsponsored investment conference 
i wont conduct foreign policy on my own kissinger said i 
wouldnt do anything without consulting the administration 
president bush has barred highlevel official trips to china as a 
sign of us displeasure with the massacre in tiananmen square the 
order extends only to executive branch officials 
nixons trip to china in february 1972 reestablished 
sinoamerican relations for the first time since the 1949 communist 
revolution he has made three other trips to china 
nixon has expressed disapproval of us sanctions saying that 
messages should be sent through private channels asking the chinese 
to show restraint 
