<TEXT>
the bush administration appealed to a powerless 
government in exile for permission to board a panamanian freighter 
off key west and was readily accommodated leading to the seizure of 
3359 pounds of cocaine the state department explained friday 
can you tell us which government gave the coast guard 
permission noriegas or the panamanian government we recognize in 
exile a reporter asked during the daily state department briefing 
the department of state requested permission from the delvalle 
government through the panamanian embassy and ambassador juan sosa 
in washington and permission was granted spokesman richard 
boucher responded 
the united states recognizes eric arturo delvalle as the 
legitimate president of panama delvalle was ousted from the office 
in february 1988 at the urging of panamas de facto ruler gen 
manuel antonio noriega 
noriega indicted by a grand jury in miami on drug trafficking 
charges also overturned the results of the may 7 election which 
showed an opposition candidate as the winner delvalle was not a 
candidate 
the united states responded to the election fraud by sending in 
american troops to bolster the 10000 or so soldiers already there 
withdrawing the us ambassador and cutting the us embassy staff 
the us coast guard boarded the panamanian freighter thursday 
night and found the hidden sacks of cocaine transportation 
secretary samuel skinner put the street value of the drugs at 1295 
million 
adm paul yost boarded the 162foot captured freighter at key 
west on friday and praised the interception saying what this 
means is that we have begun to coerce the smuggler back out on the 
sea and out of the air 
the customs service said the ships position off the direct 
route to the dominican republic aroused suspicion but an initial 
search of ship failed to turn up anything officials said 
the us state department went to the panamanian embassy in 
washington and we were given approval to go ahead and board the 
ship coast guard lt jeff karonis said in florida 
in panama government authorities said friday they were satisfied 
that the us coast guard had captured a drugrunning vessel but 
were upset that washington had gotten permission from the delvalle 
government 
we are very happy that the americans have made this capture 
said david carrera of the prosecutors office he added we are 
annoyed about the manner that they sought permission 
the united states and panama have had an antidrug agreement 
since 1976 which mandates cooperation from both sides 
in washington a reporter at the state department briefing 
pressed the issue is the united states view that the delvalle 
government in exile has the authority to grant permission for 
interception of a ship is the united states view that the delvalle 
government in exile has the authority to grant permission for any 
sort of military or paramilitary activity such as the use of coast 
guard forces to stop shipping to and from panama 
boucher said if we decide were going to try to board the 
vessel we go to the government and get permission we certainly do 
recognize the delvalle government as the government of panama and 
we recognize therefore that they have the authority to give us 
permission and then we board the vessel 
