<TEXT>
abortion advocates have staked out new jersey for the first true 
test of their punch at the polls saying theyll hit the hustings 
and slug it out on the airwaves in an allout effort to elect a 
prochoice democrat as governor 
abortion is going to be smack dab in the middle of this 
election said linda bowker state chief of the national 
organization for women with so few political races this year we 
are going to be the target state she said 
this weeks upheaval in abortion law has jarred other 1989 
campaigns particularly the virginia gubernatorial and new york 
mayoral elections but it is in new jersey that the issue has risen 
quickly to the political fore 
new jerseys race like virginias pits an antiabortion 
republican against a prochoice democrat in new york prochoice 
democratic mayor edward i koch is attacking the neutral stand of 
republican rudolph w giuliani 
people who believe in a womans right to abortion ought to 
be fearful of rudy giuliani koch has said a giuliani aide on 
wednesday accused the mayor of fearmongering 
koch began his attacks on the issue months ago but abortion 
gained new prominence as a political issue monday when the us 
supreme court approved of greater abortion restrictions by the 
states 
prochoice groups promptly pledged to fight new antiabortion 
laws and to work for the election of candidates who favor legal 
abortion in every race we will attempt to make the right to 
abortion the major issue declared now president molly yard 
the outcome is uncertain national polls have indicated that few 
voters cast their ballots solely on the issue of abortion and those 
who do split about evenly on both sides of the debate 
however given the courts ruling were dealing with a whole 
different environment said janice ballou polling director for 
the eagleton institute of rutgers university in new brunswick nj 
all those people in the middle are the ones that this change might 
impact 
in new jersey eagleton polling before the ruling found 23 
percent support for more restrictions on abortion and 68 percent 
opposing restrictions moreover many more abortion supporters held 
their views strongly 
that is promising for democratic gubernatorial nominee james 
florio who has pledged to veto any abortion restrictions and it 
may trouble republican james courter who has favored outlawing 
abortion except in most cases 
if we can have a big win for florio that makes a big 
statement said ms bowker and if we can do well in the 
assembly races that makes an even bigger statement 
her plan of attack a hit list of abortion opponents in the state 
assembly a series of prochoice rallies across the state radio 
advertising criticizing courter on the issue and two new telephone 
lines at now state headquarters in trenton 
courter for his part is playing down abortions significance 
with an aide saying wednesday he does not see it as a central issue 
in the november election 
in virginia prochoice advocates say democratic gubernatorial 
nominee l douglas wilders support for legal abortion has been 
equivocal for example he opposes public funding for abortion in 
most cases wilder faces republican j marshall coleman who opposes 
legalized abortion 
it seems to me that if doug wilders going to win he has got to 
be much stronger on the issue of womens reproductive rights said 
ms yard in washington i think hes been scared by it nobody 
wins by being scared 
in new york the issue has been raised mainly by koch against 
giuliani the frontrunner in the polls koch has had the city pay 
for abortions for poor women who have no other source of funds he 
says giuliani who opposes abortion personally cannot be trusted to 
continue the program 
but charles perkins giulianis spokesman said giuliani would 
continue the abortion funding despite his personal beliefs said 
perkins the mayor is spreading disniformation to try to heighten 
the fears of women 
abortion he said is not a mayoral issue 
