<TEXT>
a haitian exile who ran for president of his 
island nation in 1987 was arrested thursday on charges he operated a 
bogus bank that may have bilked customers out of tens of millions of 
dollars a federal prosecutor said 
clemard joseph charles who was granted asylum in the united 
states nine years ago and three others purported to run the banque 
commerciale dhaiti from a home in queens and a mortgage company 
from a luxury apartment overlooking central park in manhattan 
authorities said neither concern was authorized to operate in the 
state 
us attorney andrew j maloney said the victims of the scheme 
which ran for about two years ranged from drug dealers to 
international financiers 
what makes this operation so unusual was the brazenness the 
chutzpah maloney said they never moved out of a location they 
never left town that makes it a little extraordinary 
investigators will not know how many people and financial 
institutions were cheated and how much money the scams earned until 
records seized by fbi agents during raids thursday are examined 
maloney said 
the bank apparently cheated its customers out of tens of millions 
of dollars said assistant us attorney charles w gerber adding 
we dont really have a handle on it 
in one complex transaction the bank recently issued bogus 
multimilliondollar letters of credit payable to the palestine 
liberation organization and the economic ministries of iraq and 
libya maloney said 
the letters of credit for 2 million each from the plo and the 
two countries were used to finance the campaign of a politician from 
the dominican republic haitis neighbor on the caribbean island of 
hispaniola according to maloney 
according to court papers the scheme began to unravel last 
october when national westminster bank usa attempted to regain 
losses on a 5 million letter of credit issued by banque commercial 
dhaiti 
maloney said he could not yet explain how the phony bankers had 
managed to continue to operate without detection or retaliation 
authorities said charles 66 came to this country in 1980 after 
he was freed from a haitian jail where he spent 10 years for 
opposing former president francois papa doc duvalier charles 
was one of 35 presidential candidates in the violently aborted nov 
29 1987 general elections 
if convicted of bank fraud and other charges charles and the 
others would face at least 10 years in jail heavy fines and 
forfeiture of property purchased with their earnings maloney said 
he identified the other suspects all listed as officials of the 
bank as arthur aye 74 charles son victor 43 and peter hall 
50 all are from new york 
aye was freed on a 100000 secured bond but us magistrate 
carol bagley amon ordered the others held pending a hearing on 
tuesday 
