<TEXT>
attorneys for photographer ansel adams estate 
argued in federal court thursday that publishers of a book of adams 
pictures taken for the federal government during world war ii 
engaged in false advertising 
they sought to ban the sale of a calendar and desk reference book 
based on the same material which is entitled the mural project 
and said the book publishers wrongly used adams name to sell their 
book 
attorney thomas mustin representing the trustees of the adams 
estate said the trustees did not publish the pictures in question 
because they felt the quality was not representative of adams work 
the publishers are in it for the money mustin argued the 
trustees are in it for the reputation of ansel adams my clients 
want to preserve the integrity and quality of the work 
but attorney richard a wallen representing day dream publishing 
inc of santa barbara said the only reason the quality of the 
pictures is not good is because the negatives are unavailable the 
authors of the mural project john armor and peter wright claim 
the negatives are being hidden by the trustees 
the pictures themselves are in the public domain and can be 
purchased from the government for about 10 apiece they were shot 
in 1941 and 1942 when adams was working for the national park 
service photographing park scenes to be blown up for murals in 
public buildings the murals were never made 
interior secretary harold ickes had hired adams for 2222 a day 
plus expenses and the photos became government property 
us district judge william keller said there is no dispute that 
the photos are in the public domain and mustin said the trustees are 
not challenging publication of the book itself 
we are not challenging the book in these proceedings because we 
understand it is already in the stream of commerce he said the 
toothpaste is out of the tube 
but they seek to stop distribution of the calendar and datebook 
and further use of adams name in advertising 
the ad in question described the photos as the finding of an 
unknown body of work by ansel adams and compared it to the 
discovery of an unknown play by william shakespeare an unknown 
symphony by beethoven 
the trustees claimed this was misleading but the judge disagreed 
the fact is that this was and is a commissioned body of work 
and it was not available until the ferreting out by armor and 
wright he said im not inclined to believe from a practical 
standpoint that this is misleading advertising 
the legal arguments on further points of dispute were continued 
until friday afternoon the judge said he would take the matter 
under submission before issuing a ruling 
</TEXT>
