<TEXT>
us sugar production is rising after a slump 
because of last years drought according to agriculture department 
forecasters 
total production in the 198990 crop year that begins sept 1 is 
expected to be about 73 million tons up 56 percent from 198889 
output estimated at 691 million tons 
prompted by prices guaranteed under the governments system of 
supports and protective quotas that limit the entry of cheaper 
foreign sugar domestic output climbed to a record 733 million tons 
in 198788 
in 198586 by comparison total us sugar production was barely 
6 million tons 
with improved growing conditions sugar production in the coming 
year could match or exceed the record level of two years ago 
beet sugar production forecast at 39 million tons would be up 
11 percent from the droughtreduced level of 351 million tons this 
season the departments economic research service said thursday 
cane sugar which rose to a record of just under 34 million tons 
in 198889 is forecast at about the same in 198990 
according to field information through midjune beet planting 
and early development have generally gone well throughout the beet 
areas the report said this is in sharp contrast to last year 
when a series of spring weather problems was followed by drought in 
key eastern growing areas 
the report added drought particularly in the nonirrigated 
red river valley of western minnesota and eastern north dakota and 
disease and weather problems in california lowered yields 
these three states accounted for 55 percent of total sugar beet 
harvested acreage in 198889 and 51 percent of the total beet 
tonnage that compared with 56 percent and 54 percent respectively 
during the three previous seasons 
yields would have been even lower had it not been for good 
growing conditions late in the season excellent harvesting weather 
and higher rates of sugar recovered from the beets the report said 
farmers are expected to have about 13 million acres of beets for 
harvest in 198990 about the same as this season 
the area for sugar cane harvest is expected to be about 807000 
acres up 10 percent from 198889 reflecting small increases in 
florida louisiana and texas mainland production is forecast at 
about 245 million tons and hawaiis output 940000 tons 
hawaiis sugar cane acreage continues to contract with only 
77000 acres likely to be harvested this season compared with 
almost 100000 in the early 1980s the report said alternative 
land use continues to encroach on traditional sugar acreage 
