the ntsb on thursday issued several recommendations that would 
affect more than 80 cruise ships that dock at us ports 
only two or three such cruise ships are registered in the united 
states board investigators said 
the board which is preparing a more extensive report on the 
cruise ship industry in a few months recently concluded an 
investigation into a fire that caused a nearcatastrophe aboard a 
bahamianflagged vessel off the florida coast 16 months ago 
the board concluded that a lack of maintenance lack of 
firefighting procedures and poor crew training caused the fire 
aboard the scandinavian star which was carrying 700 people back to 
st petersburg fla from a twoday gulf of mexico cruise 
the board said failure of a firefighting system and the 
inability of crew members who spoke a variety of languages to 
communicate with each other and with passengers contributed to the 
emergency 
it was only sheer luck that no injuries or deaths occurred 
aboard the 10000ton vessel owned by sea escape of miami said ntsb 
chairman james l kolstad 
this is an invitation to disaster said kolstad he said 
usowned cruise ships are registered in several different 
countries because of the high expenses involved in meeting 
requirements as us flag carriers 
