flights to the capital of namibia because resettlement camps are 
overflowing a un spokesman said friday 
the refugees most of them supporters of the guerrilla movement 
that fought for 23 years against south african rule have stayed in 
the camps around windhoek longer than the seven days the un high 
commissioner for refugees had planned on 
un spokesman fred eckhard said the refugees are reluctant to 
leave and go to their home villages in the north where the 
southwest african peoples organization has most of its support 
because they fear namibian police will harass them 
refugees who have been flown into northern cities have moved out 
of the temporary settlement camps and those flights will continue 
eckhard said the united nations has arranged for representatives in 
the camps near windhoek to travel to the north see the situation 
and report back with the hope that the refugees in the camps will 
be persuaded to leave 
the un spokesman said 16244 of the 41000 namibians registered 
with the un high commissioner for refugees have returned so far 
mostly from swapo camps in angola and zambia 
all refugees are to return by sept 15 the end of the 
registration period for voting in elections planned for november 
