<TEXT>
drunkendriving roadblocks violate the 
rhode island constitution even if they are operated under guidelines 
the us supreme court has implied are acceptable the state supreme 
court ruled friday 
the roadblocks are an invasion of privacy under the state 
constitutions declaration of rights which is stricter than the 
federal bill of rights the high court said in a 32 decision 
police officials said the ruling would have little practical 
effect because few rhode island police departments use roadblocks 
but one police chief who favors them said the ruling could lead to 
more injuries and deaths from drunken drivers 
how about the innocent peoples rights said central falls 
police chief robert choquette who used the roadblocks until doubts 
about their constitutionality arose last summer i dont think 
its giving a fair shake to the innocent person walking down the 
street 
narragansett police capt john odonnell said his department 
abandoned the practice a couple of years ago because roadblocks were 
not costeffective and providence police capt frank devine agreed 
that his officers could catch more drunken drivers by patrolling 
than by setting up a fixed roadblock 
south kingstown police chief vincent vespia jr president of the 
rhode island police chiefs association said he does not use 
roadblocks because he agrees with the courts reasoning 
the concept of reasonable grounds to stop someone isnt there 
when you set up roadblocks to stop everybody he said 
the ruling voided the conviction of joao pimental who was found 
guilty of refusing to submit to a chemical test after he was stopped 
by warren police during a roadblock oct 10 1986 
although the us supreme court has not ruled on drunkendriving 
roadblocks it did imply in a 1979 ruling that they would be 
acceptable under certain limited conditions 
the justices agreed that the warren roadblock would probably pass 
federal muster because police gave adequate notice conducted it 
with minimal interference to the public and had limited discretion 
in deciding which cars to stop 
however chief justice thomas f fay and two other justices said 
the state constitution bars roadblocks no matter how carefully they 
are operated 
it is well beyond dispute that drunk drivers are a grave menace 
to the public and that stronger measures are needed to cope with 
this problem fay wrote however it would shock and offend the 
framers of the rhode island constitution if we were to hold that the 
guarantees against unreasonable and warrantless searches and 
seizures should be subordinated to the interest of efficient law 
enforcement 
justice donald f shea in dissent said the majority did not 
have the justifiable and principled rationale it needed to 
depart from previous us supreme court rulings 
the minimal intrusion on the drivers privacy rights is 
reasonable and fully within the safeguards provided by the rhode 
island constitution shea wrote 
</TEXT>
