president bush today asked congress to give 
some 7200 federal executives pay increases of 8 percent to 25 
percent with even higher raises going to a selected 200 with 
special skills 
however the president coupled his payraise plan with a proposal 
that the officials justify their right to the higher salaries every 
three years to be able to keep receiving them 
bushs proposal would give full 25 percent hikes to just the most 
senior officials matching a salary hike he has already advocated 
for federal judges 
more junior officials would get smaller increases at least 
initially under the plan 
the president also called for a phaseout of congressional 
peechmaking honoraria over a twoyear period and said it should be 
linked to a pay raise for lawmakers but he stopped short of 
recommending a specific level 
presidential press secretary marlin fitzwater said bush wanted 
congress to take the initiative on that politically touchy subject 
itself but that he was ready to work with congressional leaders on 
a complete package 
the plan would raise the pay of top federal officials including 
cabinet members to 124400 from the present 99500 
it would also raise the salary of vice president dan quayle from 
115000 to 143000 but it would not affect bushs 200000 salary 
the total pay package would cost taxpayers 101 million in the 
fiscal year that begins next oct 1 and 147 million in the 
following fiscal year fitzwater said 
he said the increases would be in addition to a 36 percent 
costofliving increase the president is seeking for 22 million 
federal workers 
the package would for the first time set up a special super 
category for federal employes with special talents enabling them to 
get salaries up to the 124400 top level fitzwater said 200 
individuals would qualify for these special salaries to be 
determined at a later time 
he suggested that nuclear scientists physicians or others with 
special talents would be the type of individual considered for the 
special salaries 
the most controversial part of the new package however may be 
the requirement that all members of the senior executive service 
undergo a recertification process every three years to keep their 
higher salaries 
the procedure is designed to assure that these people perform 
at a level that justifies the higher salary we do not believe it 
would weaken their rights fitzwater said 
he said the certification would not apply to the governments 700 
highlevel political appointees like cabinet members and others 
appointed by the president and confirmed by the senate because 
they can be removed at any time without appeal by the president 
