<TEXT>
new yorks program to inoculate prison 
inmates against german measles involves a choice be vaccinated or 
isolated 
prison system spokesman james flateau who has characterized the 
program as voluntary for the past several days said friday that 
12 inmates at downstate prison have refused vaccinations and have 
been kept in isolation for about a week he said the dozen 
inmates would probably remain isolated several more days until 
doctors are sure they arent going to get measles 
flateau continued to describe the rubella inoculation program 
stemming from a german measles outbreak in new york citys rikers 
island jail complex as voluntary 
it is voluntary he said theres a medical problem out 
there and youve got to address the medical problem one way of 
addressing the medical problem is to receive the inoculation the 
other way of addressing it is for us to be sure if youre not 
inoculated that you havent been exposed 
flateau said the resulting quarantines were for medical 
purposes not punitive 
the prison system spokesman said that about 20 guards have also 
refused to be vaccinated he said they are being counseled and 
that if they continue to refuse vaccinations they will be required 
to sign a waiver indicating they have been informed of the risk they 
face having signed the waiver they will be allowed to continue to 
work because they really only present a danger to each other 
said flateau the rest of the staff and all the inmates except 
those who accepted isolation will have been vaccinated 
medical isolation according to flateau means prisoners are 
confined to quarters and cant participate in group activities 
meals are brought to the prisoner 
