a storm lashed the east with powerful wind and occassionally 
heavy rain on friday toppling trees and power lines and unleashing 
thunderstorms from new york to maine 
much of the desert southwest had readings between 100 and 109 
degrees denver hit a record 100 degrees in the fourth consecutive 
day of temperatures above 100 degrees 
strong wind pushed a utility pole onto a car with four people 
inside at east rodman ny and knocked over trees and utility 
lines in port byron otisco and onondaga ny oneinch diameter 
hail fell at north tonawanda 
flooding was reported near roanoke va mount savage md and 
in parts of delaware 
other strong thunderstorms developed over western portions of the 
carolinas central texas tennessee and the lower mississippi valley 
into florida strong wind near conway ark destroyed several 
mobile homes including one that was blown onto a nearby highway 
thunderstorms were also scattered over southwestern north dakota 
where small hail was reported 
heavier rainfall during the six hours ending at 2 pm edt 
included 57 inches at lake charles la 53 inches at waco texas 
46 inches at mccomb miss and 13 inches at sioux city iowa 
temperatures began warming up across much of the nation a large 
stagnant upper level highpressure system was centered over colorado 
and contributed to the hot weather 
afternoon readings were in the 90s from the lower ohio valley 
across the middle mississippi valley the central and southern 
plains the central and southern rockies to interior california 
temperatures in the 90s also were common from florida to along 
portions of the atlantic coast 
