<TEXT>
additional inspections of older boeing 727s may be 
ordered now that airlines have found cracks on four of the planes 
according to a federal aviation administration spokesman 
the faa ordered inspections and any necessary repairs of the 47 
oldest 727s after united airlines reported it found a 20inch crack 
in one of its airplanes during a routine maintenance check june 26 
a united spokesman said thursday that tiny cracks have also been 
found on two other planes 
american airlines found a small crack on one plane the seattle 
postintelligencer reported today 
the faa deadline for completing the inspections is july 15 it 
was not known how many planes had been checked so far faa spokesman 
dave duff said 
he said that checks might be required on 405 other older 727 
aircraft built during the early 1960s because of manufacturing 
processes used at the time the postintelligencer reported 
we anticipate that we will do further airworthiness 
directives he said 
united spokesman rob doughty said two of the three united planes 
found with cracks have been repaired and are back in service and the 
third will be flying shortly 
the faas airworthiness directive sent by telegram last friday 
to 727 operators said preliminary indications are that the 
cracking was caused by fatigue 
boeing co engineers are trying to discover why the 25yearold 
united jet developed the 20inch crack in a part of its fuselage 
that hasnt been associated with high stress 
the crack was in the same general area as the rupture in an aloha 
airlines 737 that lost part of its top over hawaii last year but 
both boeing and the faa said the cracking appeared entirely 
different from that in the aloha plane 
this is a unique situation said faa spokesman duff in 
seattle this is the first time a report of cracking has been made 
in this area 
duff added the cracking was not typical of the type often found 
in older aircraft 
if not corrected the cracks in the fuselage skin could result in 
rapid decompression of the plane in flight the faa said 
duff said thursday that faa officials suspect hoop tension 
fatigue caused by outward forces against the hull in pressurized 
flight the different thicknesses of aircraft skin at the overlap 
also could be a factor he said 
the cracked segment was brought to boeing laboratories in seattle 
where engineers were trying to find why it occurred said boeing 
commercial airplanes spokesman tom cole that analysis probably will 
take several days he said 
the threeengine 727 which boeing built from 1962 to 1984 was 
the bestselling commercial jet before being surpassed by the boeing 
737 cole said 1765 727s are still in service including 41 of the 
47 planes covered by the faa order 
the april 28 1988 aloha accident in which a stewardess fell to 
her death before the flight crew could land the badly damaged plane 
focused worldwide attention on aging aircraft the 19yearold plane 
was one of the most heavily used 737s with nearly 90000 landings 
the national transportation safety board said the probable cause 
of the accident was the failure of alohas maintenance workers to 
detect significant disbonding and fatigue damage along the skin of 
the twinengine jet 
the crack in the united 727 was found where sections of skin 
overlap on the lefthand side of the plane ahead of the wings and 
below the windows duff said 
the faa order required the removal of some seats sidewall 
linings and insulation to gain access to the inside of the fuselage 
skin cole said the inspection normally could be accomplished by 
several maintenance workers in an overnight check he said 
inspections were ordered only for the 47 oldest 727s because the 
inner layer of aluminum skin was made thicker on later models cole 
said 
he said boeings decision to use the heaviergauge skin was for 
costcontrol not because the skin was too thin 
