<DOCNO> AP890707-0227 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
bond prices rallied to a twoyear high during the 
second quarter of the year but economists and analysts say they 
arent optimistic about the streak continuing through the rest of 
the year 
our feeling is that the bond market has overreacted said 
kathleen cooper chief economist for security pacific national bank 
in los angeles it tends to get carried away at times i think 
this was one of those times 
the market rally began in late march and continued through most 
of the apriljune quarter pulling the yield on the bellwether 
30year treasury bond from about 930 percent in late march to 803 
percent on june 30 bond prices move in the opposite direction from 
yields 
ms cooper believes there will be a correction in which bond 
prices will fall more in line with actual economic conditions 
she says bond traders expected the economic slowdown to be 
greater than she predicts it actually will be a slower economy is 
good for bonds because it usually eases inflation which erodes the 
value of fixedreturn investments such as bonds 
ms cooper also believes bond traders expect the federal reserve 
board will ease monetary policy more than she thinks it actually 
will the fed encourages an increase in the supply of money to 
stimulate the economy when it senses a downturn more money usually 
translates into lower interest rates which boost bond prices 
elliott platt chief economist for donaldson lufkin amp jenrette 
securities corp believes the bond rally has a few more months of 
steam left but the bulk of the rally is behind us 
he predicts the bond market would remain bullish through the 
current quarter because of continuing signs that the economy is 
slowing which eases inflation 
i think the long bond the 30year treasury is going to 
challenge and for a brief period break through the 8 percent mark 
he said last week 
but by year end he predicts the 30year treasury will be 
yielding 850 percent ms cooper was slightly more bullish 
predicting the long bond would yield 825 percent by the end of the 
year 
working in favor of bond prices in the next six months experts 
predict will be an easing of monetary policy by the fed slower 
economic growth and slower growth in the rate of inflation 
working against the market could be a depreciation in the dollar 
which could blunt the fall in inflation and limit incentives for 
foreign investors to buy us bonds which in turn would lower 
demand for the securities and soften their prices 
james kochan chief fixedincome strategist for merrill lynch amp 
co inc credits technical factors in part for this springs 
rally 
those factors he said were the popularity of zerocoupon 
treasury bonds and longmaturity municipal bonds as the supply of 
these bonds was depleted due to the demand their prices rose said 
kochan 
zerocoupon bonds lack the interestbearing portion of regular 
bonds demand for the zeros increased in the marchapril period as 
reports indicated the economy was slowing kochan said a similar 
increase in demand for longmaturity municipal bonds also pushed up 
their price he said 
since then demand for treasury zeros and long municipals has 
weakened kochan said while the supply of these securities has 
increased eliminating this as a factor in the bond market 
but kochan is more optimistic about the markets performance 
during the second half than platt and ms cooper he predicts the 
30year treasury bond will yield 775 percent by the end of the year 
as to where individual investors should put their money kochan 
recommends municipal bonds with maturities of 10 years or more as 
well as municipal zerocoupon bonds in this maturity range he also 
suggests mortgagebacked securities 
platt cautions investors who missed the bond rally to be 
disciplined and resigned to the fact that they missed 
he believes investors should avoid jumping into the longmaturity 
bond market with expectations of continued price gains instead he 
said they should buy shorterduration issues which would benefit 
more if the fed eases monetary policy 
</TEXT>
