<TEXT>
the federal reserve faced with further signs 
of a weakening economy launched a second round of credit easing 
this week even before the end of a crucial midyear review of 
monetary policy private economists said friday 
the analysts predicted that the move would send a variety of 
consumer and business interest rates lower with one saying that a 
cut in commercial banks prime lending rate could come as early as 
monday 
the fed is easing and there is clear evidence that we have 
passed the peak on interest rates said david wyss an economist 
with drimcgraw hill an economic consulting firm in lexington mass 
the development was not unexpected although some economists were 
surprised that the move came even before the end of two days of 
meetings of the federal open market committee composed of members 
of the federal reserve board in washington and five of the 12 
regional fed bank presidents 
the committee meets eight times a year to map monetary strategy 
and many had expected that the central bank would begin another 
round of easing moves in the period following this weeks meeting 
at the previous meeting held on may 16 fed policymakers 
decided to leave credit conditions unchanged they noted a variety 
of economic statistics pointing to slower growth according to 
minutes of that meeting released friday 
the nochange decision was adopted on an 111 vote with 
thomas melzer president of the federal reserve bank of st louis 
dissenting melzer argued that unless the central bank eased 
immediately it ran the danger of increasing the possibility of a 
recession 
federal reserve chairman alan greenspan will reveal details of 
this weeks discussions when he delivers the feds midyear 
assessment of the economy in congressional testimony on july 20 
david jones an economist with aubrey g lanston amp co a 
government securities dealer said the fed is acting because a 
growing number of business barometers confirm that economic growth 
is slowing 
the labor department reported friday that the nations 
unemployment rate climbed to 53 percent in june reflecting 
continued declines in manufacturing and construction the uptick in 
the jobless rate follows other statistics showing weak auto sales a 
plunge in orders for manufactured goods and lackluster retail sales 
jones said he expected the looser credit environment would mean 
that banks will cut their prime lending rate perhaps as early as 
monday banks dropped the prime to its current 11 percent in early 
june the prime rate traditinally considered a benchmark for 
business loans now influences a variety of consumer loans 
including home equity loans 
economists based their belief that the fed is easing credit on a 
slight decline in the federal funds rate which edged down 025 
percent to 925 percent in the past two days 
the federal funds rate the interest that banks charge each other 
to make overnight loans is influenced by daily decisions the 
central bank makes on how much money to make available to the 
banking system it is considered the best earlywarning signal of 
fed intentions to loosen or tighten credit conditions 
the funds rate first dropped on thursday to the 925 percent 
level and it held at that lower level on friday convincing many 
economists that the central bank had eased it would mark the second 
move toward lower interest rates in recent weeks 
the funds rate had dropped from 975 percent to 95 percent in 
early june 
greenspan and the other members of the fed have been under 
pressure from congress and the administration to let interest rates 
fall as a way of keeping the economy out of a recession 
the fed has been struggling to engineer a softlanding where 
growth slows enough to dampen inflationary pressures but without a 
recession 
wyss said he believed the odds were still 21 that the central 
bank would be successful in avoiding a recession this year 
the fed seems to be on track for a softlanding wyss said 
he said fridays unemployment report was particularly encouraging 
because it showed that average hourly earnings a good barometer of 
wage pressures showed only a moderate increase last month 
</TEXT>
