<TEXT>
britains largest union on friday called a dock 
strike starting tuesday to compel employers to continue national 
negotiations on pay and conditions 
after its dockworker members voted nearly 3to1 to strike the 
14 millionmember transport and general workers union ordered out 
its 9400 registered dockworkers and said the stoppage could last 
for months 
the strike vote was 6067 in favor and 2111 against for an 
indefinite strike to protest the employers refusal to allow 
national talks after the end of the national dock labor scheme this 
week 
dockers must understand that if they walk out not all of them 
will be coming back thats not a threat its economic reality 
said nicholas finney chairman of the national association of port 
employers 
if any registered dock worker is sacked during the course of 
the dispute there can be no return to work until he is 
reinstated countered ron todd the unions general secretary 
the employers backed by the government want a shift to local 
bargaining with the abolition july 3 of the dock labor plan at 60 
ports that handle 70 percent of britains trade by volume and 50 
percent by value 
there are 102 ports handling the remainder some employing fewer 
than 25 people 
the dock labor plan guarantees registered dockworkers a paid job 
regardless of whether they have cargoes to handle it was introduced 
during world war ii to maintain a steady work force and was made 
permanent in 1947 
the employers say the plan protected restrictive practices 
forced the employment of 12 percent more workers than needed and was 
outdated by modern cargo handling mainly gantryswung containers 
replacing the dockers hook 
modern methods have cut the registered dock workforce from 65000 
in 1967 to 9400 about 1000 more workers are employed in the 102 
nonplan ports which handle the remainder of the countrys trade 
large ports affected by the strike will include london tees and 
hartlepool immingham and grimsby forth southampton and liverpool 
most english channel ferries should escape the strike because the 
ports of dover and felixstowe are outside the plan 
the major impact of the strike is expected on movement of cars 
containerized manufactured goods newsprint timber grain 
perishable fruit animal feed iron ore and other minerals and 
chemicals 
north sea oil operators plan to switch their supply vessels from 
aberdeen and dundee in scotland to norwegian ports 
finney said more than 1000 dockworkers had quit before the 
strike accepting up to 35000 pounds or about 56700 in 
severance pay 
extensive plans have already been made by shippers and port 
customers to minimize the effect of a strike and safeguard the 
nations trade finney said 
the end of the dock labor plan means that dockworkers can be 
fired and nonunion labor can be used on waterfronts both actions 
formerly were illegal the employers have been encouraging 
dockworkers to sign individual contracts 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

